{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"05f6451e-d3ac-4979-8bbb-e66984f88361","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>`.** Here's the proof:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint> span = stackalloc nint[4];\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nLength: 4\n  span[0] = 10, span[1] = 20, span[2] = 30, span[3] = 40\nElement size: 8 bytes (native int)\n```\n\nThe `nint` (and `nuint`) types are valid `stackalloc` element types. They're unmanaged types backed by `System.IntPtr`/`System.UIntPtr`, so they satisfy the constraint. On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes; on a 32-bit runtime it would be 4.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f55c7cc3-9a75-4d5c-b31c-c580e5fe21c5","outputTokens":188,"requestId":"4BCE:21A8FE:618C217:6CB4331:69EC0E0D"},"id":"12f521fa-b966-4f2c-ac91-8bde07d6d83b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:43:00.105Z","parentId":"5a330560-f605-42b9-902a-174e441e710e"}
